Semiconductor Defect Detection¶

About Data

  • The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single production entity with associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house line testing, figure 2, and associated date time stamp. Where .1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail and the data time stamp is for that specific test point.
  • UCI - Dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/SECOM **Authors: Michael McCann, Adrian Johnston
  • Set Characteristics: Multivariate
  • Number of Instances: 1567
  • Number of Attributes: 591
  • Imbalance of the target variable: ratio of PASS to FAIL(Defect) is 97:3.

KMeans clustering with 3 clusters

In [ ]:
features_a = semi.loc[:,['Time']]
features = semi.drop(['Time','Pass/Fail'], axis=1)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=0).fit(features)

features['cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

features['cluster'].replace({0: 'Sensor0', 1: 'Sensor1', 2: 'Sensor2'}, inplace=True)
features = pd.concat([features_a, features], axis=1)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,5))
for key, grp in features.groupby(['cluster']):
    ax = grp.plot(ax=ax, kind='line', x='Time', y='0', label=key)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlim(0,200)
plt.show()

Conclusion¶

Based on the evaluation metrics, the Random Forest model appears to be the best for this particular problem, as it has the highest accuracy and F1 score among all the models. It also has a relatively high precision, indicating that it is able to correctly identify the positive class (pass) with a low false positive rate. However, it has a relatively low recall, indicating that it is not able to identify all the positive instances in the dataset. Overall, it is important to consider the specific goals and requirements of the problem when selecting the best model, as different models may be more suitable for different scenarios.

From classification reports, we can observe that Random Forest has the highest accuracy score, followed by LightGBM and then XGBoost. Random Forest also has the highest f1-score and recall for the positive class, while XGBoost has the lowest performance for the positive class. However, XGBoost has the highest precision for the positive class. LightGBM has lower performance for both precision and recall for the positive class, but has a higher precision for the negative class compared to the other models.

Overall, it is difficult to determine which model is the best without further analysis. It is important to consider the specific use case and priorities of the project to select the most appropriate model.

Final Insights¶

To improve the performance of the model in detecting defects, several strategies can be considered

  1. Feature Engineering: Using more advanced feature engineering techniques, such as feature selection or feature extraction, to improve the quality of the input data and increase the signal-to-noise ratio.

  2. Hyperparameter Tuning: Tuning the hyperparameters of the model to optimize its performance. For example, adjusting the learning rate, maximum depth, and number of estimators can improve the model's performance.

  3. Collecting more labeled data for the positive class, which can improve the model's ability to identify defects and reduce false positives.

Lessons Learned: It is important to keep in mind that improving model performance can often involve a trade-off between bias and variance. Some techniques, such as increasing the model complexity or oversampling the minority class, can reduce bias but increase variance, while others, such as regularization or early stopping, can reduce variance but increase bias. It's important to carefully evaluate the trade-offs and choose the approach that best balances bias and variance for specific problem.
